abstract: This week, Lauretta Charlton reviews Darryl Pinckney’s collection of essays “Busted in New York.” In 1992, Edmund White wrote for the Book Review about “High Cotton,” Pinckney’s debut novel about a young black man coming of age.

abstract: British lawmakers gave preliminary approval Friday to Prime Minister Boris Johnson’s Brexit bill, clearing the way for the U.K. to leave the European Union next month.
snippet: British lawmakers gave preliminary approval Friday to Prime Minister Boris Johnson’s Brexit bill, clearing the way for the U.K. to leave the European Union next month.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — British lawmakers gave preliminary approval Friday to Prime Minister Boris Johnson’s Brexit bill, clearing the way for the U.K. to leave the European Union next month.
headline_main: UK Lawmakers OK Johnson's Brexit Bill, Pave Way to Exit EU
headline_print_headline: UK Lawmakers OK Johnson's Brexit Bill, Pave Way to Exit EU

abstract: A Libyan force fighting to capture the country's capital from the U.N.-supported government based there on Friday gave the militias defending Tripoli a three-day deadline to pull out.
snippet: A Libyan force fighting to capture the country's capital from the U.N.-supported government based there on Friday gave the militias defending Tripoli a three-day deadline to pull out.
lead_paragraph: CAIRO — A Libyan force fighting to capture the country's capital from the U.N.-supported government based there on Friday gave the militias defending Tripoli a three-day deadline to pull out.
headline_main: Libyan Force Attacking Tripoli Gives Militias 3-Day Deadline
headline_print_headline: Libyan Force Attacking Tripoli Gives Militias 3-Day Deadline

abstract: As Hassan Rouhani meets with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, there was speculation that he hoped to convey a message to President Trump.
snippet: As Hassan Rouhani meets with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, there was speculation that he hoped to convey a message to President Trump.
lead_paragraph: TOKYO — President Hassan Rouhani of Iran met on Friday with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan, as speculation intensified that Mr. Abe’s friendly relations with the Iranians and the Trump administration could create a new diplomatic opening to ease tensions.

abstract: Andrew Bailey, the head of a financial regulator, will take over the role from Mark Carney.
snippet: Andrew Bailey, the head of a financial regulator, will take over the role from Mark Carney.
lead_paragraph: The British government on Friday named Andrew Bailey, the head of the Financial Conduct Authority, to be the next chief of the Bank of England. Mr. Bailey, who worked at the central bank for over 30 years before leaving to run the financial watchdog in 2016, will succeed Mark Carney.

abstract: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Dec. 20, 2019.
snippet: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Dec. 20, 2019.
lead_paragraph: An article on Thursday about the sexual exploitation and abuse of women and girls by U.N. peacekeepers in Haiti misstated Sienna Merope-Synge’s affiliation. She is a staff attorney at the Institute for Justice and Democracy in Haiti, but she is not a legal director of the Bureau des Avocats Internationaux.

abstract: There was little consensus on winners and losers, but political strategists had strong opinions on the biggest moments of the night.
snippet: There was little consensus on winners and losers, but political strategists had strong opinions on the biggest moments of the night.
lead_paragraph: Twitter can’t tell us how, or if, Thursday’s PBS/Politico debate might have changed voters’ minds. But it can give us the perspectives of some people with expertise on primary races: veteran campaign strategists and consultants from both parties.

abstract: Police banned public gatherings in parts of the Indian capital and other cities for a third day Friday and cut internet services to counter growing protests against a new law that critics say marginalizes Muslims. Fourteen people have died so far and more than 4,000 have been detained, officials said.

lead_paragraph: NEW DELHI — Police banned public gatherings in parts of the Indian capital and other cities for a third day Friday and cut internet services to counter growing protests against a new law that critics say marginalizes Muslims. Fourteen people have died so far and more than 4,000 have been detained, officials said.
headline_main: India Bans Citizenship Law Protests as Death Toll Hits 14

abstract: With wisps of smoke still rising from the remnants of another night of violence, the workers came in the morning to salvage what merchandise they could from the torched warehouses in Baghdad's central commercial district.
